## The Core Structure: How It All Fits Together
The project uses a Client-Server Architecture.
•	Analogy: Think of it like a restaurant.
•	Client (Frontend): This is the dining area where customers (users) sit. They have a menu (HTML), see the decor (CSS), and can talk to the waiter (JavaScript). It's what the user sees and interacts with.
•	Server (Backend): This is the kitchen. It takes orders from the waiter, does all the work (processes logic), gets ingredients from the storage (Database), and sends the finished food back. The customer never sees the kitchen.
•	API (Application Programming Interface): This is the waiter. The waiter's job is to take the customer's request (e.g., "I want to see all events") to the kitchen and bring the kitchen's response (the list of events) back to the customer. We used a RESTful API, which is just a standard set of rules for how the waiter should talk to the kitchen.
