## Technologies & Languages 💻
### Frontend (The Browser)
•	HTML5 (HyperText Markup Language):
o	What it is: The standard language for creating the structure of web pages.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the skeleton of your website. It defines the layout of the navbar, the hero section, the event cards, and the forms.
o	Talking Point: "We used HTML5 to build the fundamental structure and layout of all our pages, like index.html and events.html."
•	CSS3 (Cascading Style Sheets):
o	What it is: The language used to describe the presentation and styling of a web page.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the clothing and paint for the skeleton. It handles all the colors, fonts, animations, spacing, and the responsive design (making it look good on mobile).
o	Talking Point: "CSS3 was crucial for the modern look and feel, including the hover animations on buttons and the responsive grid layout for the event cards."
•	Vanilla JavaScript:
o	What it is: The programming language of the web, used to make pages interactive. "Vanilla" means we didn't use a framework like React or Angular.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the brain of the frontend. It handles fetching data from the server (using the fetch API), dynamically creating the event cards from that data (DOM Manipulation), and managing form submissions for login/registration.
o	Talking Point: "We used JavaScript's fetch API to communicate with our backend, allowing us to display live event data without ever needing to refresh the page."
### Backend (The Server)
•	Node.js:
o	What it is: A JavaScript runtime environment that lets you run JavaScript code on the server, outside of a web browser.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the engine room for our entire application. It runs the server, listens for requests from the frontend, and executes our application logic.
o	Talking Point: "Node.js was our choice for the backend because it allowed us to use JavaScript across the entire stack, making development faster and more consistent."
•	Express.js:
o	What it is: A minimal and flexible web application framework for Node.js.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the manager or traffic controller of our backend. Instead of writing complex code to handle web requests, Express gives us simple tools to define our API routes (e.g., /api/events/:id) and manage middleware.
o	Talking Point: "Express simplified our backend development immensely by providing a clear structure for creating our API routes and handling incoming requests."
### Database
•	MongoDB:
o	What it is: A popular NoSQL database that stores data in flexible, JSON-like documents.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's our digital filing cabinet. It stores our users collection (with usernames and passwords) and our events collection (with all the event details).
o	Talking Point: "We chose MongoDB because its flexible, document-based structure was perfect for storing event data, which can vary, and it integrates seamlessly with JavaScript."
•	Mongoose:
o	What it is: An Object Data Modeling (ODM) library for MongoDB and Node.js.
o	Its Role in EventRush: It's the translator or librarian that helps our Node.js server talk to the MongoDB database. It allowed us to define clear Schemas (blueprints) for our data and use simple functions like Event.find() or User.findOne() to interact with the database.
o	Talking Point: "Mongoose provided a layer of structure and validation on top of MongoDB, which helped prevent data errors and made querying our database much more straightforward."
